<text>In mathematics, the Virasoro algebra is a complex Lie algebra and the unique nontrivial central extension of the Witt algebra. It is widely used in two-dimensional conformal field theory and in string theory. It is named after Miguel Ángel Virasoro.

== Structure ==

The Virasoro algebra is spanned by generators for and the central charge .
These generators satisfy formula_1 and 

The factor of formula_2 is merely a matter of convention. For a derivation of the algebra as the unique central extension of the Witt algebra, see derivation of the Virasoro algebra.

The Virasoro algebra has a presentation in terms of two generators (e.g. 3 and −2) and six relations.

The generators formula_3 are called annihilation modes, while formula_4 are creation modes. A basis of creation generators of the Virasoro algebra&#x27;s universal enveloping algebra is the set
:formula_5
For formula_6, let formula_7, then 
formula_8.

==Representation theory==

In any indecomposable representation of the Virasoro algebra, the central generator formula_9 of the algebra takes a constant value, also denoted formula_9 and called the representation&#x27;s central charge. 

A vector formula_11 in a representation of the Virasoro algebra has conformal dimension (or conformal weight) formula_12 if it is an eigenvector of formula_13 with eigenvalue formula_12:
: formula_15 
An formula_13-eigenvector formula_11 is called a primary state (of dimension formula_12) if it is annihilated by the annihilation modes,
: formula_19 

===Highest weight representations===

A highest weight representation of the Virasoro algebra is a representation generated by a primary state formula_11.
A highest weight representation is spanned by the formula_13-eigenstates formula_22. The conformal dimension of formula_23 is formula_24, where formula_25 is called the level of formula_23.
Any state whose level is not zero is called a descendant state of formula_11.

For any formula_28, the Verma module formula_29 of central charge formula_9 and conformal dimension formula_12 is the representation whose basis is formula_22, for formula_11 a primary state of dimension formula_12. 
The Verma module is 
the largest possible highest weight representation. 
The Verma module is indecomposable, and for generic values of formula_28 it is also irreducible. When it is reducible, there exist other highest weight representations with these values of formula_28, called degenerate representations, which are quotients of the Verma module. In particular, the unique irreducible highest weight representation with these values of formula_28 is the quotient of the Verma module by its maximal submodule.

A Verma module is irreducible if and only if it has no singular vectors.

===Singular vectors===

A singular vector or null vector of a highest weight representation is a state that is both descendant and primary.

A sufficient condition for the Verma module formula_29 to have a singular vector is formula_39 for some formula_40, where 
:formula_41
Then the singular vector has level formula_42 and conformal dimension 
:formula_43
Here are the values of formula_44 for formula_45, together with the corresponding singular vectors, written as formula_46 for formula_11 the primary state of formula_48:
:formula_49
Singular vectors for arbitrary formula_40 may be computed using various algorithms, and their explicit expressions are known.

If formula_51, then formula_29 has a singular vector at level formula_53 if and only if formula_39 with formula_55. If formula_56, there can also exist a singular vector at level formula_53 if formula_58 with formula_59 and formula_60. This singular vector is now a descendant of another singular vector at level formula_42. 

The integers formula_62 that appear in formula_44 are called Kac indices. It can be useful to use non-integer Kac indices for parametrizing the conformal dimensions of Verma modules that do not have singular vectors, for example in the critical random cluster model.

===Shapovalov form===

For any formula_64, the involution formula_65 defines an automorphism of the Virasoro algebra and of its universal enveloping algebra. 
Then the Shapovalov form is the symmetric bilinear form on the Verma module formula_66 such that formula_67, where the numbers formula_68 are defined by
formula_69 and formula_70.
The inverse Shapovalov form is relevant to computing Virasoro conformal blocks, and can be determined in terms of singular vectors.

The determinant of the Shapovalov form at a given level formula_53 is given by the Kac determinant formula, 
: formula_72
where formula_73 is the partition function, and formula_74 is a positive constant that does not depend on formula_12 or formula_9. 

===Hermitian form and unitarity===

If formula_77, a highest weight representation with conformal dimension formula_12 has a unique Hermitian form such that the Hermitian adjoint of formula_79 is formula_80 and the norm of the primary state formula_11 is one. In the basis formula_82, the Hermitian form on the Verma module formula_29 has the same matrix as the Shapovalov form formula_68, now interpreted as a Gram matrix. 

The representation is called unitary if that Hermitian form is positive definite. 
Since any singular vector has zero norm, all unitary highest weight representations are irreducible.
An irreducible highest weight representation is unitary if and only if 
* either formula_85 with formula_86,
* or formula_87 with formula_88

Daniel Friedan, Zongan Qiu, and Stephen Shenker showed that these conditions are necessary, and Peter Goddard, Adrian Kent, and David Olive used the coset construction or GKO construction (identifying unitary representations of the Virasoro algebra within tensor products of unitary representations of affine Kac–Moody algebras) to show that they are sufficient.

===Characters===

